Professional Insight for Your Report

Internet service type was found to significantly influence customer churn. Fiber Optic customers exhibited a churn rate of 41.89%, substantially higher than DSL customers (18.96%) and customers without internet service (7.40%). This suggests that Fiber Optic subscribers may be experiencing service quality concerns, pricing dissatisfaction, or unmet expectations. Improving service quality and customer support for Fiber Optic users could therefore contribute significantly to reducing churn.

 Executive Summary

So far, the strongest predictors of churn are:

Month-to-Month Contracts (42.71% churn)
Fiber Optic Internet Service (41.89% churn)
Lack of Technical Support (41.64% churn)
Higher Monthly Charges

3.How long do customers typically stay active?

The typical customer stays active for:

Average: 32 months
Median: 29 months

However:

Churned customers typically leave within their first year.
Retained customers often remain for several years.
Business Insight

This finding suggests that the first year of the customer journey is critical.

If customers can be retained during their early months, they are much more likely to become long-term customers.

